@node NO10 Overview

@{b}@{u}1.0 Overview@{ub}@{uu}

This AmigaGuide® Document is formatted like this:

Section titles are in @{b}@{u}bold-underline@{ub}@{uu}.  Section sub-titles are in @{b}bold@{ub}.  Commands or options to be typed to CLI are @{fg shine}in this color@{fg text}.  Sample output from CLI is @{fg fill}in this color@{fg text}.  The @{" button-row " LINK NO10} at the bottom of each node duplicates the usual browser commands for easy keyboard browsing.

This document is meant to be displayed with the @{b}XHelvetica @{ub}and @{b}XCourier @{ub}fonts included in the MagicWB package.  With other fonts, this document is still readable but the indentation might appear incorrect.

1.1	@{" Requirements " LINK NO11}
1.2	@{" The Story " LINK NO12}
1.3	@{" Installation " LINK NO13}

@{"Back to Main Index" LINK MAIN 7}
@endnode

@node NO11 "Requirements"
@toc NO10

@{b}1.1 Requirements@{ub}

Stringer needs AmigaOS 2.1 (V37) or later and a minimum of 25 kb's of free mem to operate.  Stringer is pure and can be made resident.

For searching in archives you need the corresponding unarchiving utility (LhA, UnZip, etc.) in your search path and to display text files you need a text viewer (More, Less, Most, etc.).

@{" Back to Main Index " LINK MAIN 7} @{" Back to Overview Index " LINK NO10} @{" Next Topic " LINK NO12}
@endnode

@node NO12 "The Story"
@toc NO10

@{b}1.2 The Story @{ub}

Yes, yet another Search replacement ... with bells on it.  As it happens, I wrote this purely for my own usage and amusement and was surprised to see that there were so many similar utils already out there.  This one started its life as a tool for counting strings, mainly very short strings (as in counting the relative frequencies of the alphabets) and it just grew from there.

The current version of Stringer, however, is not just a Search replacement.  It is a powerful search and replace tool with a large number of options to get the desired results.  Currently Stringer has among others the following features:

 -	Stringer can search for any number of multiple strings
 -	Strings can be of any size and they can be substrings of other strings searched for and they can be
	read from a file
 -	Search and Replace capability for multiple source and destination strings with optional individual
	prompting and backups
 -	Can search for strings in archive files (.lha, .zip, etc.)
 -	Can hunt for files using file names or file comments
 -	Search statistics for matched strings:  match counts, relative space usage and relative frequencies
 -	Can start a pager for immediate viewing of the matched file
 -	Various options for modifying the output to your needs
 -	Complete emulation of C:Search with identical ouput if so desired
 -	Comprehensive documentation with multiple examples and on-line help
 -	Fastest operation of any utility of this kind (see the @{" test section " LINK NO40})

@{" Back to Main Index " LINK MAIN 7} @{" Back to Overview Index " LINK NO10} @{" Next Topic " LINK NO13}
@endnode

@node NO13 "Installation"
@toc NO10

@{b}1.3 Installation @{ub}

For an easy installation execute the installation script provided with the archive.

To install Stringer manually:

1. Copy the executable to somewhere in your Path:
@{fg shine}Copy Stringer C:@{fg text}
2. Copy one of the provided default preferences to ENV: and ENVARC:
@{fg shine}Copy Stringer.prefs ENV:
Copy Stringer.prefs ENVARC:@{fg text}

@{" Back to Main Index " LINK MAIN 7} @{" Back to Overview Index " LINK NO10} @{" Next Topic " LINK NO20}
@endnode

@node NO20 "Usage"

@{b}@{u}2.0 Usage@{ub}@{uu}

Stringer is run from the CLI with the basic command line looking like this:

@{fg shine}Stringer SOURCEFILES STRINGS [OPTIONS]@{fg text}

Stringer behaves exactly like Search with its default options so you can immediately use it as you did Search before.

For a quick help about command line options start Stringer from CLI without any options.

2.1	@{" Command line options " LINK NO21}
2.2	@{" Output control " LINK NO22}
2.3	@{" Script file usage " LINK NO23}
2.4	@{" Preferences " LINK NO24}
2.5	@{" Example ARexx scripts " LINK NO25}

@{" Back to Main Index " LINK MAIN 10}
@endnode

@node NO21 "Command line options"
@toc NO20

@{b}2.1 Command line options@{ub}

To see more on an option or for a related example click the More button.

@{u}More	Option			Description@{uu}

Required options:

  @{"   " LINK NO31}	@{fg shine}FROM/M/A@{fg text}		- Source files to search from
  @{"   " LINK NO31}	@{fg shine}SEARCH/A@{fg text}		- Strings to search or a file name containing the strings
					   Separate strings with "," in CLI or "<CR>" in a file

Output modifiers:

  @{"   " LINK "N=NONUM, This is the only info available"}	@{fg shine}N=NONUM/S@{fg text}		- No line numbering, faster search
  @{"   " LINK NO35}	@{fg shine}L=NOLINES/S@{fg text}		- Don't show lines were a match was found
  @{"   " LINK NO32}	@{fg shine}Q=QUICK/S@{fg text}		- Less CR's in the CLI output
  @{"   " LINK NO33}	@{fg shine}O=ONLY/S@{fg text}		- Show only names of files where a match was found
  @{"   " LINK NO22}	@{fg shine}ANSI/S@{fg text}			- Highlight matched string in the output
  @{"   " LINK NO22}	@{fg shine}FC=FILECOL/K/N@{fg text}	- Color for filenames (a pen number from 0 to n)
  @{"   " LINK NO22}	@{fg shine}HC=HITCOL/K/N@{fg text}		- Color for a matched string (a pen number from 0 to n)
  @{"   " LINK NO22}	@{fg shine}QU=QUIET/S@{fg text}		- No output to CLI, only a result code

Extra information options:

  @{"   " LINK NO35}	@{fg shine}V=VERBOSE/S@{fg text}		- Show file size and number and size of strings
  @{"   " LINK NO35}	@{fg shine}T=SHOWTIME/S@{fg text}		- Show elapsed time
  @{"   " LINK NO33}	@{fg shine}M=MATCHES/S@{fg text}		- Show number of matches in current file
  @{"   " LINK NO38}	@{fg shine}R=REPORT/S@{fg text}		- Print out a full report of what was found and where
  @{"   " LINK NO35}	@{fg shine}S=STATS/S@{fg text}		- Display search statistics
  @{"   " LINK NO37}	@{fg shine}AS=ALLSTATS/S@{fg text}	- Just like STATS but for multiple files

General options:

  @{"   " LINK NO46}	@{fg shine}B=BUFFER/K/N@{fg text}		- Work buffer size in kilobytes, defaults to 100 kb
  @{"   " LINK NO33}	@{fg shine}C=CASE/S@{fg text}			- Case sensitive search
  @{"   " LINK NO31}	@{fg shine}A=ALL/S@{fg text}			- Recursively scan the file tree
  @{"   " LINK "I=INVERT, This is the only info available"}	@{fg shine}I=INVERT/S@{fg text}		- Show lines that do not match the search criteria
  @{"   " LINK NO34}	@{fg shine}P=PATTERN/S@{fg text}		- SEARCH is an AmigaDOS pattern
  @{"   " LINK NO36}	@{fg shine}F=FILE/S@{fg text}			- Hunt for a filename, SEARCH=filename to search for
  @{"   " LINK NO36}	@{fg shine}FN=FILENOTE/S@{fg text}	- Hunt for a filenote, SEARCH=filenote to search for
  @{"   " LINK NO38}	@{fg shine}BIN/S@{fg text}			- Force Stringer to search through binary files.
  @{"   " LINK NO22}	@{fg shine}MH=MAXHIT/K/N@{fg text}	- Give up on a file when MAXHIT matches are found
  @{"   " LINK NO35}	@{fg shine}SF=STRFILE/S@{fg text}		- Load strings from a file, SEARCH=filename
  @{"   " LINK NO24}	@{fg shine}NP=NOPREFS/S@{fg text}		- Ignore ENV:Stringer.prefs
  @{"   " LINK NO310}	@{fg shine}ARC/S@{fg text}			- Also search through archive files (.lha, .zip, etc.)
  @{"   " LINK NO311}	@{fg shine}SHOW/S@{fg text}			- Call up a text viewer to view the matched file
  @{"   " LINK NO312}	@{fg shine}H=HELP/K@{fg text}			- Displays information on an option

Replace options:

  @{"   " LINK NO39}	@{fg shine}RE=REPLACE/K@{fg text}		- Replace matched strings with these strings
  @{"   " LINK NO39}	@{fg shine}ASK/S@{fg text}			- Ask before replacing
  @{"   " LINK NO39}	@{fg shine}SAFE/S@{fg text}			- Replace to a new file without deleting the old one
  @{"   " LINK NO39}	@{fg shine}OW=OVERWRITE/S@{fg text}	- Overwrite in REPLACE

Yup, a lot of command line options.  If this seems a bit overwhelming just browse through the @{" command line examples " LINK NO30} and all will be clear.

@{" Back to Main Index " LINK MAIN 10} @{" Back to Usage Index " LINK NO20} @{" Next Topic " LINK NO22}
@endnode

@node NO22 "Output control"
@toc NO20

@{b}2.2 Output control@{ub}

Specifying the @{fg shine}L=NOLINES@{fg text} option means that you won't get any output on your screen.  So, use it only in combination with the @{fg shine}M=MATCHES@{fg text} and/or @{fg shine}S=STATS@{fg text} options.  Using the @{fg shine}QU=QUIET@{fg text} option, you won't get any output at all except the error messages not even the filenames.  Using the @{fg shine}O=ONLY@{fg text} option displays only the file names where a match was found so, in effect, this is the same as specifying @{fg shine}L=NOLINES@{fg text}, @{fg shine}M=MATCHES@{fg text} and @{fg shine}Q=QUICK@{fg text}, the output, however, looks different in each case.

The options @{fg shine}R=REPORT@{fg text} and @{fg shine}AS=ALLSTATS@{fg text} are immune to the @{fg shine}QU=QUIET@{fg text} option.  This is in the likely case you would want to see nothing but the reports.

Use the @{fg shine}ANSI@{fg text} option to add some color to your output.  You can control the colors with the @{fg shine}FC=FILECOL@{fg text} and @{fg shine}HC=HITCOL@{fg text} options.

Note that if you use the @{fg shine}MH=MAXHIT@{fg text} and @{fg shine}S=STATS@{fg text} options together the stats won't be correct since the search is aborted when @{fg shine}MH=MAXHIT@{fg text} hits are found.

While Stringer is running you can abort the search with @{fg shine}CTRL-C@{fg text} or you can skip the current file with @{fg shine}CTRL-D@{fg text}.

@{" Back to Main Index " LINK MAIN 10} @{" Back to Usage Index " LINK NO20} @{" Next Topic " LINK NO23}
@endnode

@node NO23 "Script file usage"
@toc NO20

@{b}2.3 Script file usage@{ub}

Stringer exits with these return codes:
0 = One or more match found
5 = No matches found
20 = A fatal error occurred

Use Stringer in a script file like this:

@{fg fill}--- AmigaDOS script file ---
Failat 20

Stringer Text.doc PoroJesse QUIET

If warn
	Echo "Didn't find PoroJesse in Text.doc."
Else
	Echo "Found the string PoroJesse in Text.doc !"
EndIf
--- AmigaDOS script file ---@{fg text}

@{" Back to Main Index " LINK MAIN 10} @{" Back to Usage Index " LINK NO20} @{" Next Topic " LINK NO24}
@endnode

@node NO24 "Preferences"
@toc NO20

@{b}2.4 Preferences@{ub}

Stringer reads your preferences from a file called ENV:Stringer.prefs.  The format of the file is this:  the first line contains your default command line options and the second line contains your @{" default pager " LINK NO24 19} and the lines after that are used to handle the different @{" archive formats " LINK NO24 39} used.

@{fg fill}--- Example ENV:Stringer.prefs file ---
ANSI MAXHIT=200 QUICK BUFFER=400 SAFE
MyPager -l %u "%f"
.pp	ppdecrunch "%s" "" COLOR 4 QUIET
.lzh	lha -q e "%s"
.lha	lha -q e "%s"
.lzx	lzx -q x "%s" >NIL:
.zip	unzip -o -qq "%s" >NIL:
--- Example ENV:Stringer.prefs file ---@{fg text}


2.4.1 Your default pager

In the second line you set your default pager (a utility that can display text files for you, for example, Less, MuchMore, PPShow, Most, Vinci, AmigaGuide or MultiView).  In this line the formatting commands are replaced as follows:  %f is replaced with the name of the text file, %s is replaced with the string we found, %ld is replaced with the byte offset where in this text file the string was found for the first time and %u is replaced with the line number where the string was found.  So, @{fg fill}Pager -b %ld "%f" @{fg text}would result in a command line like @{fg fill}Pager -b 24365 "mytext.txt" @{fg text}being executed when Stringer starts your pager for you.  @{fg fill}Pager -l %u "%f"@{fg text} would result in a similar execution but instead of the byte offset of the match the line number of the match is used.

After Stringer starts your pager for you it will wait until the pager exits.  You can change this behaviour with adding a Run command to the start of your default pager command line.

For another approach take a look at the @{" example ARexx scripts " LINK NO25} provided in Stringers distribution archive for Most and Vinci.

See @{" Command Line Example 11 " LINK NO311} for how to use this option.


2.4.2 Different archive formats

In the third and the following lines you define the archive formats Stringer can use.  Currently Stringer recognizes the .pp .lzh .lha .lzx and .zip formats and calls the PPDecrunch, LhA, LZX and UnZip utilities to unpack these archives.  So, these utils have to be in your search path for this option to work.  If you want to add more archive formats you have to edit the ENV:Stringer.prefs file.  Format for an archive line in this file is:

@{fg fill}.suffix<TAB>commandline_to_extract_to_current_dir<CR>@{fg text}

In the command line you give in this file the formatting command %s is replaced with the archive name.  Do not use archivers that automatically delete the original packed file after decrunching it (e.g.,  some versions of uncompress and gzip).  If you do, you will lose your archive forever.

You would usually want to redirect the archiver's output to >NIL: but if you want to see the actual unpacking information in your CLI you can leave out the output redirection.  Also disable any interactivity your unpacker might have (e.g., asking if you want to replace these files, create directories, etc.).

@{" Command Line Example 10 " LINK NO310} illustrates further how to use this option.


2.4.3 Setting your preferences

To set your preferences for Stringer edit or create the ENV:Stringer.prefs file with any text editor, which can handle ASCII text.

To make your prefs permanent do this:

@{fg shine}Copy ENV:Stringer.prefs ENVARC:Stringer.prefs@{fg text}

Your preferred command line options are read in first and then your command line options are 'added' to these.  To temporarily disable your preferred command line options use the command line option @{fg shine}NOPREFS@{fg text}.

@{" Back to Main Index " LINK MAIN 10} @{" Back to Usage Index " LINK NO20} @{" Next Topic " LINK NO25}
@endnode

@node NO25 "Example ARexx scripts"
@toc NO20

@{b}2.5 Example ARexx scripts@{ub}

Since most pagers (well, almost all of them, shame on you text viewer coders =) don't sport a command line option for jumping directly into a certain place in the text file viewed you can instead of starting the pager directly start an ARexx script.  Some pagers have an ARexx port and most of them have an ARexx command for jumping to a specific place in a text file.  So, you'll need some ARexx knowledge to make Stringer play ball with these CLI challenged pagers.

These are example scripts on how to use a text viewer's ARexx port to display a text file for you.  Take a look at them if you are interested in making your preferred text viewer jump to the correct location in the text file being viewed.  There is no need for a separate ARexx script if you don't mind that your text viewer always starts at the beginning of the file.

@{" Example script for Most " LINK start_most.rexx/main}
@{" Example script for Vinci " LINK start_vinci.rexx/main}

@{" Back to Main Index " LINK MAIN 10} @{" Back to Usage Index " LINK NO20} @{" Next Topic " LINK NO30}
@endnode


